Read-in and clean

We can use code from last practical to read in and clean our data. Note that the code below is a condensed version of what we did last week but it does the same job.

library(tidyverse)
# read in
gensex <- read_csv("https://mivalek.github.io/adata/gen_sex_q.csv")


### AGE

# recode age and gender
gensex <- gensex %>%
  mutate(Age = recode(Age, "18 years" = "18", "19 years old" = "19"),
         Age = as.numeric(Age),
         Gender = factor(Gender))

# count how many cases you're about to remove
age_removed <- gensex %>% filter(Age > 99) %>% nrow()

# count how many you're about to remove
all_missing <- gensex %>% filter(rowSums(is.na(gensex)) > 10) %>% nrow()

# remove them
gensex <- gensex %>% filter(Age < 100 & rowSums(is.na(gensex)) < 11)


# DESCRIPTIVES ------------------------------------------------------------

# desc for Age

age_desc <- gensex %>%
  summarise(mean = mean(Age, na.rm = T),
            sd = sd(Age, na.rm = T),
            min = min(Age, na.rm = T),
            max = max(Age, na.rm = T)) %>%
  modify(round, 2)

# Break-down of gender with age stats
gen_age_desc <- gensex %>%
  mutate(Gender = fct_explicit_na(Gender)) %>%
  group_by(Gender) %>%
  summarise(n = n(),
            perc = n()/nrow(gensex) * 100,
            mean_age = mean(Age, na.rm = T),
            sd_age = sd(Age, na.rm = T))

Visualisation

While some descriptive statistics and results are best summarised in a table, it is often worth visualising your data using plots. Some plots are great for presenting results to your audience while others are just a tool for you to get a better feel for your data and results. It is neither necessary nor desirable to include every plot you create in your write-up/paper/poster. Only show plots if they add anything of explanatory value to your body text and tables, the rest are for your eyes only (or for the appendix/supplementary materials).

Lets look at a simple histogram of our Age variable:

gensex %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Age)) +
  geom_histogram()
`stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

OK, this histogram gives us a visual representation of the distribution of ages in the sample: The vast majority of participants are 18-19 years old. This is not news as we can read this from the first summary we ran:

As you can see the first quartile of age is 19 and the third quartile is 20. That means that at least the middle 50% of the samples age falls within 19 and 20. Seeing the distribution plotted is, however, still useful.

Aesthetically speaking, our histogram isnt that much to look at. Fortunately, with ggplot() and some of its extensions, we can customise our plots to death and beyond! The cowplot package contains a nice clean theme for publication-style ggplot() plots. Lets install it.

install.packages("cowplot")

Once we load it, we can add theme_cowplot() to our plot to make it look a little better:

library(cowplot)
gensex %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Age)) +
  geom_histogram() +
  theme_cowplot()
`stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

Notice that R warns us that the histogram plots values by default into 30 bins. In other words, it leaves enough room in the plot for 30 columns. However, we only have 8 distinct ages (17-24). We might as well change the number of bins to 8 using the bins= argument inside geom_histogram(). While we are at it, we can also change the colour of the outline of the bars (color=) and the colour of the bars themselves (fill=):

library(cowplot)
gensex %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Age)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 8, color = "black", fill = "grey") +
  theme_cowplot()

That looks way better! The only thing left to do now is give our axes proper labels:

library(cowplot)
gensex %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Age)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 8, color = "black", fill = "grey") +
  labs(x = "Age in years", y = "Frequency") +
  theme_cowplot()

There, thats one neat plot!

OK, lets see what we can do with our Gender variable.

Basically the only way of visualising a single categorical variable is using the barchart:

gensex %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Gender)) +
  geom_bar()

Again, we can customise the plot in several ways. Notice that the bars are ordered alphabetically and their labels are the same as the levels of our Gender variable:

gensex %>%
  pull(Gender) %>%
  levels()
[1] "Female" "Male"   "Other"

Lets tweak the appearance of our plot using what we already know:

gensex %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Gender)) +
  geom_bar(color = "black", fill = "grey") +
  labs(x = "Gender", y = "N") +
  theme_cowplot()

I think this is a rather nice plot!

If you really care about the small things and want to replace the NA with something more explicit, you can use the fct_explicit_na() function that turns NA into (Missing) by default (but this can be changed to whatever you want). Again, because were essentially changing the variable, the command needs to be inside mutate():

gensex %>%
  mutate(Gender = fct_explicit_na(Gender)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Gender)) +
  geom_bar(color = "black", fill = "grey") +
  labs(x = "Gender", y = "N") +
  theme_cowplot()

Note that the mutate() command comes before the data are pushed into ggplot(). That is because we arent really changing the plot itself but the gensex tibble. We are essentially telling R to temporarily modify the Gender variable in the tibble before it gets used for plotting.

Next, we can visualise the age breakdown by gender choice using boxplots. To do this, you need to map each both of these variables onto one axis inside of the aes() function: The categorical variable belongs on the x axis and the continuous on the y axis:

gensex %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Gender, y = Age)) +
  geom_boxplot()

We can re-use essentially all the commands from our previous plot to make this boxplot by group a little nicer.

gensex %>%
  mutate(Gender = fct_explicit_na(Gender)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Gender, y = Age)) +
  geom_boxplot(color = "black", fill = "grey") +
  labs(x = "Gender", y = "Age in years") +
  theme_cowplot()

Thats it for descriptive plots. Lets build up a more interesting plots that will show us something about the relationships between the main measured variables.

Suppose we are interested in knowing whether there is a relationship between participants self-ratings of masculinity and femininity. If these are inverses of each other as is sometimes claimed, the dots should be pretty much lined up: the more masculine you think you are, the less feminine you consider yourself. However, these dimensions may well not be opposites of one another. If thats the case, it is possible for a person to feel both highly masculine and feminine at the same time. Lets build a plot to find out.

Since both of these variables are continuous, a scatterplot is probably the best option. In ggplot(), we create scatterplots using geom_pooint():

gensex %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Gender_fem_1, y = Gender_masc_1)) +
  geom_point()

OK, there is definitely a moderate-to-strong negative relationship between a persons masculinity and femininity self-rating but its hardly perfect. Some people are relatively high on both of these dimensions!

The plot also looks like we only have a handful of observations because the points are drawn on top of each other. We can jitter them around to get a better reflection of our sample size. Now, jittering points makes the plot lie a little about the actual values people chose but the trade-off is that the sample size shows better.

gensex %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Gender_fem_1, y = Gender_masc_1)) +
  geom_point(position = "jitter")

Thats better.

Now, lets say we want to know if the relationship looks the same for each level of the Gender variable. We can choose to colour the points by gender. Since were mapping a variable, we need to do this as an sthetic using the aes() function:

gensex %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Gender_fem_1, y = Gender_masc_1, colour = Gender)) +
  geom_point(position = "jitter")

Finally, we can change the look of the plot a little. Lets make the points a little larger using the size= argument and ever so slightly transparent (alpha= goes from 0 to 1). Then add better axis labels and change the theme of the plot.

gensex %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Gender_fem_1, y = Gender_masc_1, colour = Gender)) +
  geom_point(position = "jitter", size = 2, alpha = .4) +
  labs(x = "Femininity", y = "Masculinity") +
  theme_cowplot()

Thats a nice one!

Its interesting to see that different gender categories display different patters. While participants who reported their gender as female seem to be roughly spread across the diagonal of the plot, those who reported their gender as male a seem to be distributed more flatly in the top half of the plot. Unfortunately, we do not have enough data from participants in the Other category to make any observations.

Please bear in mind that we cannot really say for certain if these differences are statistically significant just by looking at the scatterplot. For that, we need to run some tests!

This is just about enough plotting for one day. If youve been typing along, save your script.

Over to you!
